Make Fake Album Cover Game

Table of Contents¶

Our goal is to create randomly generated album covers with:

  1. Learn how to use the function display_cover
  2. Loading a random page from Wikipedia
  3. Extracting the Title of the Article
  4. Displaying the Album Cover

Estimated Time Needed: 60 min

Inspiration: Fake Album Covers

Import libraries¶

In [1]:
from IPython.display import Image as IPythonImage
from PIL import Image
from PIL import ImageFont
from PIL import ImageDraw

Helper function to superimpose text on image¶

In [2]:
def display_cover(top,bottom ):
    """This fucntoin
    """
    import requests
    
    name='album_art_raw.png'
    # Now let's make get an album cover.
    # https://picsum.photos/ is a free service that offers random images.
    # Let's get a random image:
    album_art_raw = requests.get('https://picsum.photos/500/500/?random')
    # and save it as 'album_art_raw.png'
    with open(name,'wb') as album_art_raw_file:
       album_art_raw_file.write(album_art_raw.content)
    # Now that we have our raw image, let's open it 
    # and write our band and album name on it
    img = Image.open("album_art_raw.png")
    draw = ImageDraw.Draw(img)

    # We'll choose a font for our band and album title, 
    # run "% ls /usr/share/fonts/truetype/dejavu" in a cell to see what else is available,
    # or download your own .ttf fonts!
    band_name_font = ImageFont.truetype("/usr/share/fonts/truetype/dejavu/DejaVuSans-Bold.ttf", 25) #25pt font
    album_name_font = ImageFont.truetype("/usr/share/fonts/truetype/dejavu/DejaVuSans-Bold.ttf", 20) # 20pt font

    # the x,y coordinates for where our album name and band name text will start
    # counted from the top left of the picture (in pixels)
    band_x, band_y = 50, 50
    album_x, album_y = 50, 400

    # Our text should be visible on any image. A good way
    # of accomplishing that is to use white text with a 
    # black border. We'll use the technique shown here to draw the border:
    # https://mail.python.org/pipermail/image-sig/2009-May/005681.html
    outline_color ="black"

    draw.text((band_x-1, band_y-1), top, font=band_name_font, fill=outline_color)
    draw.text((band_x+1, band_y-1), top, font=band_name_font, fill=outline_color)
    draw.text((band_x-1, band_y+1), top, font=band_name_font, fill=outline_color)
    draw.text((band_x+1, band_y+1), top, font=band_name_font, fill=outline_color)

    draw.text((album_x-1, album_y-1), bottom , font=album_name_font, fill=outline_color)
    draw.text((album_x+1, album_y-1), bottom , font=album_name_font, fill=outline_color)
    draw.text((album_x-1, album_y+1), bottom , font=album_name_font, fill=outline_color)
    draw.text((album_x+1, album_y+1), bottom , font=album_name_font, fill=outline_color)

    draw.text((band_x,band_y),top,(255,255,255),font=band_name_font)
    draw.text((album_x, album_y),bottom,(255,255,255),font=album_name_font)

    return img

1) Learn how to use the function display_cover ¶

The function display_cover selects a random image from https://picsum.photos/ and will help us superimpose two strings over the image. The parameter top is the string we would like to superimpose on the top of an image. The parameter bottom is the string we would like to display on the bottom of the image. The function does not return the image but returns an object of type Image from the Pillow library; the object represents a PIL image.

In [3]:
img=display_cover(top='top',bottom='bottom')

To save the image, we use the method save . The argument is the file name of the image we would like to save in this case 'sample-out.png'

In [4]:
img.save('sample-out.png')

Finely we use IPythonImage to read the image file and display the results.

In [5]:
IPythonImage(filename='sample-out.png')
Out[5]:
In [ ]:

Question 1) Use the display_cover function to display the image with the name Python on the top and Data Science on the bottom. Save the image as 'sample-out.png'.

In [6]:
img=display_cover(top='Python',bottom='Data Science')
In [7]:
img.save('sample-out.png')
In [8]:
IPythonImage(filename='sample-out.png')

Part 2: Loading a random page from Wikipedia ¶

In this project, we will use the request library, we used it in the function display_cover, but you should import the library in the next cell.

In [9]:
import requests

The following is the URL to the page

In [10]:
wikipedia_link='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:Random'
In [11]:
snist='http://103.15.62.28/student/?value=finalmarksreport&tab=allmarks&studentid=26258'

Question 2) Get Wikipedia page is converted to a string

Use the function get from the requests library to download the Wikipedia page using the wikipedia_link as an argument. Assign the object to the variable raw_random_wikipedia_page.

In [12]:
raw_random_wikipedia_page=requests.get(wikipedia_link)
In [13]:
snistpage=requests.get(snist)

Use the data attribute text to extract the XML as a text file a string and assign the result variable page:

In [14]:
pageload=snistpage.text
print(pageload)

<p><b>Chalat</b> (<a href="/wiki/Persian_language" title="Persian language">Persian</a>: <span lang="fa" dir="rtl"></span>&#8206;, also <a href="/wiki/Romanize" class="mw-redirect" title="Romanize">Romanized</a> as <b>Chelat</b>; also known as <b>Kalt</b>)<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> is a village in <a href="/wiki/Qilab_Rural_District" title="Qilab Rural District">Qilab Rural District</a>, <a href="/wiki/Alvar-e_Garmsiri_District" title="Alvar-e Garmsiri District">Alvar-e Garmsiri District</a>, <a href="/wiki/Andimeshk_County" title="Andimeshk County">Andimeshk County</a>, <a href="/wiki/Khuzestan_Province" title="Khuzestan Province">Khuzestan Province</a>, <a href="/wiki/Iran" title="Iran">Iran</a>. At the 2006 census, its population was 65, in 14 families.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>
</p>

Part 3: Extracting the Title of the Article ¶

Question 3 (part 1) Use the title of the Wikipedia article as the title of the band. The title of the article is surrounded by the XML node title as follows: <title>title - Wikipedia</title> . For example, if the title of the article was Python we would see the following: <title>Python - Wikipedia</title>. Consider the example where the title of the article is Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles the result would be: <title>Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles - Wikipedia</title>. The first step is to find the XML node <title> and </title>indicating the start and end of the title. The string function find maybe helpful, you can also use libraries like xlxml.

In [16]:
title=page.find('<title>')
#print(title)
title2=page.find('</title>')
#print(title2)
print(page[101:136])

Chalat - Wikipedia</title>
<script>

Question 3 (part 2) Next get rid of the term - Wikipedia from the title and assign the result to the band_title For example you can use the function or method strip or replace.

	<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">Pages (band)</h1>
	
	<div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content">
		<div id="siteSub" class="noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
		<div id="contentSub"></div>
		
		
		
		<div id="jump-to-nav"></div>
		<a class="mw-jump-link" href="#mw-head">Jump to navigation</a>
		<a class="mw-jump-link" href="#p-search">Jump to search</a>
		<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="mw-parser-output"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">For other bands or groups with similar name, see <a href="/wiki/Page_(disambiguation)" class="mw-redirect mw-disambig" title="Page (disambiguation)">Page</a>.</div>
<table class="infobox vcard plainlist" style="width:22em"><tbody><tr><th colspan="2" style="text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold;background-color: #b0c4de"><div style="display:inline;" class="fn org">Pages</div></th></tr><tr><td colspan="2" style="text-align:center"><a href="/wiki/File:Pages_(band).jpg" class="image"><img alt="Pages (band).jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/5/51/Pages_%28band%29.jpg/220px-Pages_%28band%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="150" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/5/51/Pages_%28band%29.jpg/330px-Pages_%28band%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/5/51/Pages_%28band%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="382" data-file-height="261" /></a><div>Pages circa 1979; from left to right: Charles "Icarus" Johnson, Steve George, Jerry Manfredi, Richard Page and George Lawrence</div></td></tr><tr><th colspan="2" style="text-align:center;background-color: #b0c4de">Background information</th></tr><tr><th scope="row">Origin</th><td><a href="/wiki/Los_Angeles" title="Los Angeles">Los Angeles</a>, <a href="/wiki/California" title="California">California</a>, United States</td></tr><tr><th scope="row">Genres</th><td><div class="hlist hlist-separated"><ul><li><a href="/wiki/Pop_rock" title="Pop rock">Pop rock</a></li><li><a href="/wiki/Soft_rock" title="Soft rock">soft rock</a></li></ul></div> <sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup></td></tr><tr><th scope="row"><span class="nowrap">Years active</span></th><td>19781981</td></tr><tr><th scope="row">Labels</th><td><div class="hlist hlist-separated"><ul><li><a href="/wiki/Epic_Records" title="Epic Records">Epic</a></li><li><a href="/wiki/Capitol_Records" title="Capitol Records">Capitol</a></li></ul></div></td></tr><tr><th scope="row"><span class="nowrap">Associated acts</span></th><td><div class="hlist hlist-separated"><ul><li><a href="/wiki/Mr._Mister" title="Mr. Mister">Mr. Mister</a></li><li><a href="/wiki/Third_Matinee" title="Third Matinee">Third Matinee</a></li></ul></div></td></tr><tr><th colspan="2" style="text-align:center;background-color: #b0c4de"></th></tr><tr><th scope="row">Members</th><td><a href="/wiki/Richard_Page_(musician)" title="Richard Page (musician)">Richard Page</a><br /><a href="/wiki/Steve_George_(keyboardist)" title="Steve George (keyboardist)">Steve George</a><br />Peter Leinheiser<br />Jerry Manfredi<br />Russ Battelene<br />John Lang<br /><a href="/wiki/Charles_Foster_Johnson" title="Charles Foster Johnson">Charles "Icarus" Johnson</a><br />George Lawrence</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p><b>Pages</b> was an American <a href="/wiki/Pop_rock" title="Pop rock">pop rock</a> band active during the late 1970s and the early 1980s.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>
<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>
<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>  The band consisted of <a href="/wiki/Richard_Page_(musician)" title="Richard Page (musician)">Richard Page</a> and <a href="/wiki/Steve_George_(keyboardist)" title="Steve George (keyboardist)">Steve George</a> on vocals and keyboards supported by various studio musicians, some of whom from time to time were considered part of the band. Although Pages was highly regarded for its well-crafted pop and jazz-fusion sound, the group did not achieve commercial success, and disbanded after recording only three <a href="/wiki/Studio_album" class="mw-redirect" title="Studio album">studio albums</a>. Pages is perhaps best known as the launching pad for the recording careers of Page and George, who later formed the band <a href="/wiki/Mr._Mister" title="Mr. Mister">Mr. Mister</a>, who topped the charts during the mid-1980s with pop classics such as "<a href="/wiki/Broken_Wings_(Mr._Mister_song)" title="Broken Wings (Mr. Mister song)">Broken Wings</a>" and "<a href="/wiki/Kyrie_(song)" title="Kyrie (song)">Kyrie</a>".
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Origins">Origins</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Pages_(band)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Origins">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Pages grew out of a long friendship between Richard Page and Steve George, dating back to their high school days in <a href="/wiki/Phoenix,_Arizona" title="Phoenix, Arizona">Phoenix, Arizona</a>. After high school, the two occasionally played together in bands in <a href="/wiki/Los_Angeles" title="Los Angeles">Los Angeles</a> and <a href="/wiki/Las_Vegas_Valley" title="Las Vegas Valley">Las Vegas</a>. For a time, Page relocated to San Diego to attend music school.
</p><p>In 1977, emerging teen idol <a href="/wiki/Andy_Gibb" title="Andy Gibb">Andy Gibb</a>, recently relocated in Los Angeles and as his first single, "<a href="/wiki/I_Just_Want_to_Be_Your_Everything" title="I Just Want to Be Your Everything">I Just Want to Be Your Everything</a>," was racing to the top of the charts, recruited Page and George to perform vocals and keyboards as part of his backing band along with Peter Leinheiser on lead guitar, Jerry Manfredi on bass and Russ Battelene on drums.
</p><p>Gibb toured with this group of musicians throughout 1977.  Toward the end of the year, the group recorded a demo tape of original jazz-fusion material.  This tape came to the attention of former <a href="/wiki/Blood,_Sweat_%26_Tears" title="Blood, Sweat &amp; Tears">Blood, Sweat &amp; Tears</a> drummer <a href="/wiki/Bobby_Colomby" title="Bobby Colomby">Bobby Colomby</a>, who liked what he heard and signed the group, now called "Pages," to <a href="/wiki/Epic_Records" title="Epic Records">Epic Records</a>.  The group also included Page's cousin John Lang.  Although Lang could not play a musical instrument (he claimed he was tone deaf), he became Pages' chief lyricist.
</p>
<h2><span id="Pages_.281978.29"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Pages_(1978)"><i>Pages</i> (1978)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Pages_(band)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Pages (1978)">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Pages' <a href="/wiki/Eponym" title="Eponym">eponymous</a> first album, released in 1978, featured tracks ranging from light funk ("Clearly Kim"), calypso ("Love Dance") and driving rock ("Room At The Top") to smooth, harmonious ballads ("This Is For The Girls," "I Get It From You") and luscious instrumentals ("Interlude").
</p><p>The album featured an impressive array of session musicians.  The roster of talent included Colomby, Philip Bailey (Earth, Wind &amp; Fire), Steve Forman, Dave Grusin, Claudio Slon, Victor Feldman and Michael Brecker.  Although Page provided most of the lead vocals, George took the lead on "Let It Go" and "Listen For The Love."
</p><p>Colomby was quoted as saying that "Pages represents the mainstream of contemporary music. They utilize various elements and combine them into an original and tasty mixture that will appeal to all formats of radio."  Despite Colomby's prediction, radio found it hard to place the group's sound.  Neither <i>Pages</i> nor its single "If I Saw You Again" made the Billboard charts.  Leinheiser and Battelene went their own way after the album was recorded.
</p>
<h2><span id="Future_Street_.281979.29"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Future_Street_(1979)"><i>Future Street</i> (1979)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Pages_(band)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Future Street (1979)">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>After the commercial failure of their debut album, Pages went back to the studio to record their 1979 follow-up, entitled <i>Future Street</i>.  <a href="/wiki/Charles_Foster_Johnson" title="Charles Foster Johnson">Charles "Icarus" Johnson</a> joined on acoustic and electric guitar, and George Lawrence was brought in on drums.
</p><p>According to Page, "Jerry [Manfredi], Steve [George] and myself were writing all the music but it just didn't sound right. Everybody knew it, but it was left unspoken for a long time because of that lingering bond. With Charles and George everything went perfect for the first time. The potential was just staring us in the face".
</p><p>Once again produced by Colomby, the album blended the finely crafted overtones of the first album with a somewhat hard-edged pop-rock sound with progressive overtones.  Additional musicians and artists on <i>Future Street</i> included Kenny Loggins (backing vocals and songwriting on "Who's Right Who's Wrong"), George Hawkins, Joey Trujillo, Jai Winding and Steve Lukather. George took lead vocals on "Two People." Another detail is that the cover sleeve was designed by John Lang.
</p><p>The opening track, the energetic "I Do Believe In You," peaked at number 84 on the Billboard Hot 100 in December 1979.
</p>
<h2><span id="Pages_.281981.29"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Pages_(1981)"><i>Pages</i> (1981)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Pages_(band)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Pages (1981)">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Although <i>Future Street</i> displayed future commercial potential, the album failed to chart.  Now down to a duo of Page and George (with long-time collaborator Lang still aboard as non-performing lyricist) the band switched to <a href="/wiki/Capitol_Records" title="Capitol Records">Capitol Records</a>, and brought in acclaimed producer <a href="/wiki/Jay_Graydon" title="Jay Graydon">Jay Graydon</a>.  The resulting album - eponymous like their first album - was released in 1981.  Two singles were released from the album, "You Need a Hero" and "Come on Home."  These were the only tracks produced by Bobby Colomby on the album.
</p><p>The players on this album consisted of Page (lead and background vocals), George (backing vocals, Fender Rhodes, synthesizer: Yamaha CS-80 - Oberheim - ARP 2600, Mini-Moog, clavinet, electric power oboe and grand piano), John Lang (co-writer), Charles Johnson (guitar), Neil Stubenhaus (bass), Ralph Humphrey (drums), Steve Khan (electric guitar), Jeff Porcaro (drums), Paulinho DaCosta (percussion), Vince Colaiuta (drums), Tom Scott (sax), Jay Graydon (guitars, synthesizer programming, producer), Mike Baird (drums) and Al Jarreau (vocal flute).  Despite this powerhouse lineup of musicians, the album failed to chart.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="After_Pages">After Pages</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Pages_(band)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: After Pages">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>With the commercial failure of yet a third album, Page and George decided to disband the group, returning to the session circuit as highly sought-after songwriters and backing vocalists.
</p><p>They recorded with well-known producers like <a href="/wiki/David_Foster" title="David Foster">David Foster</a> and <a href="/wiki/Quincy_Jones" title="Quincy Jones">Quincy Jones</a>.  They performed on albums by <a href="/wiki/Al_Jarreau" title="Al Jarreau">Al Jarreau</a>, <a href="/wiki/Donna_Summer" title="Donna Summer">Donna Summer</a>, <a href="/wiki/Chaka_Khan" title="Chaka Khan">Chaka Khan</a>, <a href="/wiki/REO_Speedwagon" title="REO Speedwagon">REO Speedwagon</a>, <a href="/wiki/Kenny_Loggins" title="Kenny Loggins">Kenny Loggins</a>, <a href="/wiki/Pointer_Sisters" class="mw-redirect" title="Pointer Sisters">Pointer Sisters</a>, <a href="/wiki/Molly_Hatchet" title="Molly Hatchet">Molly Hatchet</a> and <a href="/wiki/Twisted_Sister" title="Twisted Sister">Twisted Sister</a>. Richard and Steve also did the vocals for <a href="/wiki/Village_People" title="Village People">Village People</a>, together with <a href="/wiki/Chicago_(band)" title="Chicago (band)">Chicago's</a> <a href="/wiki/Bill_Champlin" title="Bill Champlin">Bill Champlin</a> and Tom Kelly (songwriter of Madonna's world hit "<a href="/wiki/Like_a_Virgin_(song)" title="Like a Virgin (song)">Like a Virgin</a>").  Page was also part of the well-known back-up vocal trio of that also included Kelly and <a href="/wiki/Tommy_Funderburk" title="Tommy Funderburk">Tommy Funderburk</a>.
</p><p>By 1982, Page and George decided to form a more pop-oriented band with permanent members.  As one-half of the four-piece band <a href="/wiki/Mr._Mister" title="Mr. Mister">Mr. Mister</a>, they would achieve commercial success with the Number One singles "Broken Wings" and "Kyrie" in the mid-1980s.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Covers_of_Pages_songs">Covers of Pages songs</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Pages_(band)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Covers of Pages songs">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>A number of artists have covered Pages songs.  
</p><p><a href="/wiki/Kenny_Loggins" title="Kenny Loggins">Kenny Loggins</a> covered "Who's Right, Who's Wrong" on his 1979 album <i><a href="/wiki/Keep_The_Fire" class="mw-redirect" title="Keep The Fire">Keep The Fire</a></i>, with <a href="/wiki/Michael_Jackson" title="Michael Jackson">Michael Jackson</a> providing backing vocals.
</p><p><a href="/wiki/America_(band)" title="America (band)">America</a> recorded "I Do Believe In You" on their 1980 album, <i><a href="/wiki/Alibi_(America_album)" title="Alibi (America album)">Alibi</a></i>. <sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>  <a href="/wiki/Frank_Stallone" title="Frank Stallone">Frank Stallone</a> also covered that song on his self-titled debut album from 1984.
</p><p><a href="/wiki/Herb_Alpert" title="Herb Alpert">Herb Alpert</a> recorded "I Get It From You" on his 1981 album, <i>Magic Man</i>. <sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>  In 1979, <a href="/wiki/Bobby_Hutcherson" title="Bobby Hutcherson">Bobby Hutcherson</a> covered "The Sailor's Song" as a <a href="/wiki/Vibraphone" title="Vibraphone">vibraphone</a>-driven instrumental on his <i><a href="/wiki/Un_Poco_Loco_(album)" title="Un Poco Loco (album)">Un Poco Loco</a></i> album. <sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 2011, multi-instrumentalist Zo! recorded a <a href="/wiki/Slow_jam" title="Slow jam">slow jam</a> rendition of "Let It Go" on his <a href="/wiki/Extended_play" title="Extended play">EP</a> <i>...Just Visiting Three</i> with vocals by Nicholas Ryan Grant.
</p><p>Also in 2011, electronic artist <a href="/wiki/Vektroid" title="Vektroid">Vektroid</a> released her album <a href="/wiki/Floral_Shoppe" title="Floral Shoppe">Floral Shoppe</a> under the pseudonym Macintosh Plus, on which "If I Saw You Again" from Pages' first self-titled album <sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> and "You Need a Hero" from their second self-titled album <sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> are sampled. <sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>
</p>

<tbody><tr style="line-height: 1.4em;">
<td style="width: 33%; text-align: center; vertical-align: top; padding: .2em .1em .2em 0;">"<a href="/wiki/Sorry_(Justin_Bieber_song)" title="Sorry (Justin Bieber song)">Sorry</a>" <br />(2015)
</td>
<td style="width: 33%; text-align: center; vertical-align: top; padding:.2em .1em;">"<b>Love Yourself</b>" <br />(2015)
</td>
<td style="width: 33%; text-align: center; vertical-align: top; padding: .2em 0 .2em .1em;">"<a href="/wiki/Company_(Justin_Bieber_song)" title="Company (Justin Bieber song)">Company</a>" <br />(2016)
</td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" style="text-align:center"></td></tr><tr><th colspan="2" style="text-align:center;background:khaki">Music video</th></tr><tr><td colspan="2" style="text-align:center"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oyEuk8j8imI"><span class="plainlinks">"Love Yourself"</span></a> on <a href="/wiki/YouTube" title="YouTube">YouTube</a></td></tr><tr style="display:none"><td colspan="2">
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>"<b>Love Yourself</b>" is a song recorded by Canadian singer <a href="/wiki/Justin_Bieber" title="Justin Bieber">Justin Bieber</a> for his fourth studio album <i><a href="/wiki/Purpose_(Justin_Bieber_album)" title="Purpose (Justin Bieber album)">Purpose</a></i> (2015). The song was released first as a promotional single on November 9, 2015, and later was released as the album's third single. It was written by <a href="/wiki/Ed_Sheeran" title="Ed Sheeran">Ed Sheeran</a>, <a href="/wiki/Benny_Blanco" title="Benny Blanco">Benny Blanco</a> and Bieber, and produced by Blanco. An <a href="/wiki/Acoustic_music" title="Acoustic music">acoustic</a> <a href="/wiki/Pop_music" title="Pop music">pop</a> song, "Love Yourself" features an <a href="/wiki/Electric_guitar" title="Electric guitar">electric guitar</a> and a brief flurry of <a href="/wiki/Trumpets" class="mw-redirect" title="Trumpets">trumpets</a> as its main instrumentation. During the song, Bieber uses a husky tone in the lower registers. Lyrically, the song is a <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/kiss-off" class="extiw" title="wikt:kiss-off">kiss-off</a> to a narcissistic ex-lover who did the protagonist wrong.
</p><p>On the US <a href="/wiki/Billboard_Hot_100" title="Billboard Hot 100"><i>Billboard</i> Hot 100</a> and the <a href="/wiki/UK_Singles_Chart" title="UK Singles Chart">UK Singles Chart</a>, the song became Bieber's third consecutive number-one, where in the United States it spent 24 non-consecutive weeks in the top ten (later named the <a href="/wiki/Billboard_Year-End_Hot_100_singles_of_2016" title="Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 2016">best-performing single of 2016</a>) and was also Bieber's first number one on the <a href="/wiki/Adult_Contemporary_(chart)" title="Adult Contemporary (chart)">Adult Contemporary</a> chart, while in the United Kingdom it spent six weeks at the top. "Love Yourself" topped the charts in fifteen countries, including Australia, Canada, New Zealand, and Sweden. "Love Yourself" was nominated for two <a href="/wiki/Grammy_Awards" class="mw-redirect" title="Grammy Awards">Grammy Awards</a>: <a href="/wiki/Grammy_Award_for_Song_of_the_Year" title="Grammy Award for Song of the Year">Song of the Year</a> and <a href="/wiki/Grammy_Award_for_Best_Pop_Solo_Performance" title="Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance">Best Pop Solo Performance</a>. It was the seventh-best-selling song of 2016 in the US.<sup id="cite_ref-ussales_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ussales-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The music video for the song was released along with the Purpose: The Movement project on November 14, 2015. It features a couple doing an <a href="/wiki/Interpretive_dance" title="Interpretive dance">interpretive dance</a> in their house. Bieber promoted the song with performances on TV shows, as well as awards shows throughout 201516, while adding it on the set list of his <a href="/wiki/Purpose_World_Tour" title="Purpose World Tour">Purpose World Tour</a>.
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Background_and_release">Background and release</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Love_Yourself&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Background and release">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Ed_Sheeran_(8508821340).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Ed_Sheeran_%288508821340%29.jpg/170px-Ed_Sheeran_%288508821340%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="170" height="253" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Ed_Sheeran_%288508821340%29.jpg/255px-Ed_Sheeran_%288508821340%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Ed_Sheeran_%288508821340%29.jpg/340px-Ed_Sheeran_%288508821340%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1000" data-file-height="1486" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Ed_Sheeran_(8508821340).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Ed Sheeran <i>(pictured)</i> initially wrote "Love Yourself" for his album <i><a href="/wiki/%C3%B7_(album)" title=" (album)"></a></i> before giving it to Bieber.</div></div></div>
<p>On September 29, 2015, Justin Bieber announced in an interview with Australia's <a href="/wiki/Sunrise_(Australian_TV_program)" title="Sunrise (Australian TV program)">Sunrise</a> morning show that British singer and songwriter <a href="/wiki/Ed_Sheeran" title="Ed Sheeran">Ed Sheeran</a> had written a song for his then-upcoming album.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Later, during an interview for <a href="/wiki/Capital_(radio_network)" title="Capital (radio network)">Capital FM</a>, Bieber revealed details about the song, saying: "It's just me and a guitar. Basically that's how I started, playing on the street with a guitar." About Sheeran, he said: "I think he's one of the most talented writers in the game right now, so just to have his input and his stories and our stories and match them up together and say 'What have you been through?,' and telling the same story."<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> In another interview for the same radio network, he commented about the collaboration, stating: "It was a process. Just getting us together, you know, in the same room cause we did a lot of it separate. He is a good guy, super talented. Really good songwriter so just to be able to work with that calibre of songwriter was really, really awesome."<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> In 2017, Sheeran revealed that "Love Yourself" was written for his album <i><a href="/wiki/%C3%B7_(album)" title=" (album)"></a></i>. He said in an interview that the track would have been scrapped before Bieber took the song.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On November 9, 2015 "Love Yourself" premiered on <i><a href="/wiki/Beats_1" title="Beats 1">Beats 1</a></i> along with "The Feeling".<sup id="cite_ref-cosmo_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cosmo-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> The song was also made available on <a href="/wiki/ITunes" title="ITunes">iTunes</a> in the same day as a promotional single of <i>Purpose</i>,<sup id="cite_ref-rollingstone_1-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rollingstone-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> and later it was announced as the album's official third radio single.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> When talking to <a href="/wiki/Ryan_Seacrest" title="Ryan Seacrest">Ryan Seacrest</a>, Bieber said "Love Yourself" is "definitely about someone in my past, someone who I don't want to put on blast," he described the song as "cool because so many people can resonate with that because how many women do we bring back that mom doesn't really necessarily like?."<sup id="cite_ref-crest_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-crest-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Composition_and_lyrics">Composition and lyrics</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Love_Yourself&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Composition and lyrics">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<table role="presentation" class="mbox-small-left noprint" style="background-color:#f9f9f9;border:1px solid #aaa;color:#000;float:left">
<tbody><tr>
<td class="mbox-image"><div class="center"><div class="floatnone"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/87/Gnome-mime-sound-openclipart.svg/50px-Gnome-mime-sound-openclipart.svg.png" decoding="async" width="50" height="50" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/87/Gnome-mime-sound-openclipart.svg/75px-Gnome-mime-sound-openclipart.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/87/Gnome-mime-sound-openclipart.svg/100px-Gnome-mime-sound-openclipart.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="160" data-file-height="160" /></div></div></td>
<td class="mbox-text plainlist" style="line-height:1.1em"><div class="haudio">
<div style="padding:4px 0"><a href="/wiki/File:Justin_Bieber_-_Love_Yourself.ogg" title="File:Justin Bieber - Love Yourself.ogg">"Love Yourself"</a></div>
<div><div class="mediaContainer" style="width:220px"><audio id="mwe_player_0" controls="" preload="none" style="width:220px" class="kskin" data-durationhint="23.248979591837" data-startoffset="0" data-mwtitle="Justin_Bieber_-_Love_Yourself.ogg" data-mwprovider="local"><source src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/9/96/Justin_Bieber_-_Love_Yourself.ogg" type="audio/ogg; codecs=&quot;vorbis&quot;" data-title="Original Ogg file (59 kbps)" data-shorttitle="Ogg source" data-width="0" data-height="0" data-bandwidth="58821" /><source src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/transcoded/9/96/Justin_Bieber_-_Love_Yourself.ogg/Justin_Bieber_-_Love_Yourself.ogg.mp3" type="audio/mpeg" data-title="MP3" data-shorttitle="MP3" data-transcodekey="mp3" data-width="0" data-height="0" data-bandwidth="168208" /><track src="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=TimedText:Justin_Bieber_-_Love_Yourself.ogg.en.srt&amp;action=raw&amp;ctype=text%2Fx-srt" kind="subtitles" type="text/x-srt" srclang="en" label="English (en) subtitles" data-mwtitle="TimedText:Justin_Bieber_-_Love_Yourself.ogg.en.srt" data-mwprovider="local" data-dir="ltr" /></audio></div></div>
<div class="description" style="padding:2px 0 0 0">A 23-second sample of "Love Yourself"'s <a href="/wiki/Refrain" title="Refrain">chorus</a>, which Bieber described as relatable and "cool".<sup id="cite_ref-crest_11-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-crest-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup></div></div></td></tr>
<tr><td colspan="2" class="mbox-text" style="line-height:1.1em"><hr /><i class="selfreference">Problems playing this file? See <a href="/wiki/Help:Media" title="Help:Media">media help</a>.</i></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>"Love Yourself" was written by <a href="/wiki/Ed_Sheeran" title="Ed Sheeran">Ed Sheeran</a>, <a href="/wiki/Benny_Blanco" title="Benny Blanco">Benny Blanco</a> and <a href="/wiki/Justin_Bieber" title="Justin Bieber">Justin Bieber</a>, with production being done by <a href="/wiki/Benny_Blanco" title="Benny Blanco">Benny Blanco</a>, who was also responsible for the song's instrumentation and programming. It features background vocals by Sheeran. According to the sheet music published at Musicnotes.com by <a href="/wiki/Sony/ATV_Music_Publishing" title="Sony/ATV Music Publishing">Sony/ATV Music Publishing</a>, the song is composed in the <a href="/wiki/Key_(music)" title="Key (music)">key</a> of <a href="/wiki/E_major" title="E major">E major</a> with a moderate <a href="/wiki/Tempo" title="Tempo">tempo</a> of 100 <a href="/wiki/Tempo" title="Tempo">beats per minute</a> and a <a href="/wiki/Time_signature" title="Time signature">time signature</a> of <span style="font-family: &#39;Georgia Pro&#39;, Georgia, &#39;DejaVu Serif&#39;, Times, &#39;Times New Roman&#39;, serif;"><span style="display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:0.85em;font-size:80%;text-align:center"><sup style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline"><b>4</b></sup><br /><sub style="font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline"><b>4</b></sub></span></span>. Bieber's vocals range from the note of <a href="/wiki/B_(musical_note)" title="B (musical note)">B<sub>2</sub></a> to <a href="/wiki/B_(musical_note)" title="B (musical note)">B<sub>4</sub></a>.<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> It is an <a href="/wiki/Acoustic_pop" class="mw-redirect" title="Acoustic pop">acoustic pop</a> song, featuring just vocals, an <a href="/wiki/Electric_guitar" title="Electric guitar">electric guitar</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-rollingstone_1-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rollingstone-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-umc_13-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-umc-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> and a brief flurry of <a href="/wiki/Trumpets" class="mw-redirect" title="Trumpets">trumpets</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-spin1_14-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-spin1-14">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> which was considered "the most subdued and least electronic of Bieber's new tracks."<sup id="cite_ref-rollingstone_1-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rollingstone-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Lyrically, "Love Yourself" is a <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/kiss-off" class="extiw" title="wikt:kiss-off">kiss-off</a> to a narcissistic ex-lover who did the protagonist wrong,<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-cosmo_9-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cosmo-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> with Bieber singing in a snappy and spiteful tone<sup id="cite_ref-Pearce_16-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Pearce-16">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup> while "hating on a girl for loving herself too much."<sup id="cite_ref-teenvogue_17-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-teenvogue-17">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> In the pre-chorus, he sings with a husky tone in the lower registers:<sup id="cite_ref-Pearce_16-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Pearce-16">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup> "My mama don't like you, and she likes everyone," "in a style that molds well to Sheeran's," according to <i><a href="/wiki/Rolling_Stone" title="Rolling Stone">Rolling Stone</a></i><span class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">&#39;s</span> Brittany Spanos.<sup id="cite_ref-rollingstone_1-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rollingstone-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> "And I [never] like to admit that I was wrong. And I've been so caught up in my job, didn't see what's going on, and now I know, I'm better sleeping on my own," he continues.<sup id="cite_ref-rollingstone_1-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rollingstone-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> In the chorus, Bieber sings, "Cause if you like the way you look that much, oh baby you should go and love yourself,"<sup id="cite_ref-teenvogue_17-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-teenvogue-17">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> which according to <a href="/wiki/Digital_Spy" title="Digital Spy">Digital Spy</a>'s Amy Davidson, "'love yourself' means 'go f**k yourself' in this context."<sup id="cite_ref-Davidson_18-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Davidson-18">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup> On March 7, 2017, composer Ed Sheeran stated on the Howard Stern Show that he had Rihanna in mind for the song at first, and the original lyric was indeed "fuck yourself".<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup> In the song's bridge, Bieber uses a "<a href="/wiki/Vocalese" title="Vocalese">brass-and-vocalese</a>" style.<sup id="cite_ref-CMac_20-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CMac-20">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Critical_reception">Critical reception</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Love_Yourself&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Critical reception">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Andrew Unterberger of <i><a href="/wiki/Spin_(magazine)" title="Spin (magazine)">Spin</a></i> called it "an earth-salting, cruelly chuckling kiss-off track, it features an unprecedented-for-Bieber caliber of lyrical detail, and its minimal arrangement allows every lyrical barb to pop like one of the song's palm-mutes. For such sour grapes, though, 'Love Yourself' still sounds exultant; one of many reminders this year that for all his insistence on being a good person, Bieber may ultimately be best served as a <a href="/wiki/Top_40" title="Top 40">Top 40</a> heel."<sup id="cite_ref-spin1_14-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-spin1-14">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> Leah Greenblatt of <i><a href="/wiki/Entertainment_Weekly" title="Entertainment Weekly">Entertainment Weekly</a></i> complimented the track as one of her favourites from the album, naming it "the world's first campfire-folk <a href="/wiki/Diss_track" class="mw-redirect" title="Diss track">diss track</a>."<sup id="cite_ref-Greenblatt_21-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Greenblatt-21">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup> Amy Davidson of <a href="/wiki/Digital_Spy" title="Digital Spy">Digital Spy</a> agreed, calling it a 'deliciously evil poison-pen ballad'.<sup id="cite_ref-Davidson_18-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Davidson-18">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup> Sheldon Pearce of <i><a href="/wiki/Complex_(magazine)" title="Complex (magazine)">Complex</a></i> praised "<a href="/wiki/Sorry_(Justin_Bieber_song)" title="Sorry (Justin Bieber song)">Sorry</a>" and "Love Yourself" for "display[ing] the best of Bieber in tandem: the full scope of his pop stylingsblue-eyed soul fleshing out both electronic and acoustic spaces."<sup id="cite_ref-Pearce_16-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Pearce-16">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup> Kenneth Partridge of <i><a href="/wiki/Billboard_(magazine)" title="Billboard (magazine)">Billboard</a></i> wrote that Bieber "overplay[s] his renewed spirituality ... mak[ing] like <a href="/wiki/John_Mayer" title="John Mayer">John Mayer</a> doing <a href="/wiki/Sam_Smith_(singer)" title="Sam Smith (singer)">Sam Smith</a>," citing the track as an example.<sup id="cite_ref-Partridge_22-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Partridge-22">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup> Josh Gonzalez of Music Times thought the song was "a cool change of pace and nod musically to his 2014 duet with <a href="/wiki/Cody_Simpson" title="Cody Simpson">Cody Simpson</a> '<a href="/wiki/Home_to_Mama" title="Home to Mama">Home to Mama</a>'," adding: "Bieber is a great vocalist and does well on acoustic tracks."<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>For <i><a href="/wiki/Consequence_of_Sound" title="Consequence of Sound">Consequence of Sound</a></i> editor Janine Schaults, "all the credit goes to <a href="/wiki/Ed_Sheeran" title="Ed Sheeran">Sheeran</a>'s cherubic magic powers. Refreshingly, just a guitar and a lonely trumpet interlude accompany Bieber's coy delivery."<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">&#91;24&#93;</a></sup> Michelles Geslani of the same publication opined that the track "sounds exactly what you'd expect from a meeting of these two minds," considering it "'<a href="/wiki/Thinking_Out_Loud_(Ed_Sheeran_song)" class="mw-redirect" title="Thinking Out Loud (Ed Sheeran song)">Thinking Out Loud</a>' crossed with low-key, lovelorn Bieber."<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup> Kitty Empire, writing for <i><a href="/wiki/The_Observer" title="The Observer">The Observer</a></i>, appreciated the song for "strip[ping] everything back very effectively to a guitar line and a vocal."<sup id="cite_ref-Empire_26-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Empire-26">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup> Annie Zaleski of <i><a href="/wiki/The_A.V._Club" title="The A.V. Club">The A.V. Club</a></i> was mixed, noting that "despite being a nicely deadpan kiss-off to a snobby ex, is generic acoustic-pop."<sup id="cite_ref-Zaleski_27-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Zaleski-27">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup> In a less favorable review, <a href="/wiki/Pitchfork_Media" class="mw-redirect" title="Pitchfork Media">Pitchfork</a>'s Brad Nelson wrote that, lyrically, "it's needlessly mean, neither funny nor clever, and it doesn't do much to justify the severity of its perspective."<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup> Al Horner of <i><a href="/wiki/NME" title="NME">NME</a></i> noted that the song is "more traditionally Bieber, and [its] big pop hook [is] out of place amidst the forward-thinking electronic scuttle."<sup id="cite_ref-Horner_29-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Horner-29">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup> Sam C. Mac of <a href="/wiki/Slant_Magazine" title="Slant Magazine">Slant Magazine</a> called the lyrics "unintentionally hilarious."<sup id="cite_ref-CMac_20-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CMac-20">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup> Alex Macpherson of <i><a href="/wiki/The_National_(Abu_Dhabi)" title="The National (Abu Dhabi)">The National</a></i> called it "a cloying Ed Sheeran collaboration."<sup id="cite_ref-Macpherson_30-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Macpherson-30">&#91;30&#93;</a></sup> <i><a href="/wiki/Billboard_(magazine)" title="Billboard (magazine)">Billboard</a></i> ranked "Love Yourself" at number 34 on their "100 Best Pop Songs of 2016" list.<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Chart_performance">Chart performance</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Love_Yourself&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Chart performance">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="United_States">United States</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Love_Yourself&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: United States">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:242px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Justin_Timberlake_-_The_2020_Experience_World_Tour_-_Charlotte,_North_Carolina_03.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/Justin_Timberlake_-_The_2020_Experience_World_Tour_-_Charlotte%2C_North_Carolina_03.jpg/240px-Justin_Timberlake_-_The_2020_Experience_World_Tour_-_Charlotte%2C_North_Carolina_03.jpg" decoding="async" width="240" height="180" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/Justin_Timberlake_-_The_2020_Experience_World_Tour_-_Charlotte%2C_North_Carolina_03.jpg/360px-Justin_Timberlake_-_The_2020_Experience_World_Tour_-_Charlotte%2C_North_Carolina_03.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/Justin_Timberlake_-_The_2020_Experience_World_Tour_-_Charlotte%2C_North_Carolina_03.jpg/480px-Justin_Timberlake_-_The_2020_Experience_World_Tour_-_Charlotte%2C_North_Carolina_03.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1984" data-file-height="1488" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Justin_Timberlake_-_The_2020_Experience_World_Tour_-_Charlotte,_North_Carolina_03.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Bieber became the first male artist since <a href="/wiki/Justin_Timberlake" title="Justin Timberlake">Justin Timberlake</a> <i>(pictured)</i> in 2006 to achieve three number-ones in the US from an album.</div></div></div>
<p>In the United States, the song debuted at number four on the <a href="/wiki/Billboard_Hot_100" title="Billboard Hot 100"><i>Billboard</i> Hot 100</a>, giving Bieber his ninth top ten song and his third consecutive top ten debut from <i>Purpose</i>. It also debuted at number two and four on the <a href="/wiki/Digital_Songs" title="Digital Songs">Digital Songs</a> and <a href="/wiki/Streaming_Songs" title="Streaming Songs">Streaming Songs</a> charts, respectively, with 141,000 downloads and 17.4&#160;million streams.<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">&#91;32&#93;</a></sup> The following week, it descended to number seven on the Hot 100.<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup> Two weeks later, it ascended from seven to five on the Hot 100, meanwhile Bieber's "<a href="/wiki/Sorry_(Justin_Bieber_song)" title="Sorry (Justin Bieber song)">Sorry</a>" and "<a href="/wiki/What_Do_You_Mean%3F" title="What Do You Mean?">What Do You Mean?</a>" were at number two and four, respectively. Thus, as he did three weeks prior when "Love Yourself" debuted at number four, Bieber had three concurrent songs in the Hot 100's top five, becoming the third act to achieve it since <a href="/wiki/50_Cent" title="50 Cent">50 Cent</a> in 2005. Bieber and <a href="/wiki/The_Beatles" title="The Beatles">The Beatles</a> are the only acts to earn the honor as a lead artist on all three songs.<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup> On the chart dated February 6, 2016, "Love Yourself" ascended from three to two on the Hot 100, meanwhile Bieber's "Sorry" was at number one. With the feat, Bieber became the 17th act in the Hot 100's history to rank at numbers one and 2 simultaneously. He was also the 11th act to hold the Hot 100's top two as a lead artist on both songs.<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The following week, "Love Yourself" replaced "Sorry" at number one, becoming his third consecutive number-one single. Thus, Bieber was the 12th artist to succeed himself in the Hot 100's 57-year history; the last artist before Bieber was <a href="/wiki/The_Weeknd" title="The Weeknd">The Weeknd</a>, who is also from Canada. Additionally, Bieber's <i>Purpose</i> became the first album by a male artist to produce three number-one songs since <a href="/wiki/Justin_Timberlake" title="Justin Timberlake">Justin Timberlake</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/FutureSex/LoveSounds" title="FutureSex/LoveSounds">FutureSex/LoveSounds</a></i> did so in 200607.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup> After being replaced at the top of the Hot 100 by <a href="/wiki/Zayn_Malik" title="Zayn Malik">Zayn</a>'s debut single as a solo artist, "<a href="/wiki/Pillowtalk_(song)" title="Pillowtalk (song)">Pillowtalk</a>", for one week, it returned to the number one position the following date. Also, "Love Yourself" replaced "Sorry" at the top of the <a href="/wiki/Radio_Songs" class="mw-redirect" title="Radio Songs">Radio Songs</a> chart with 144 million weekly audience, becoming Bieber's second number-one song on the chart.<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup> However, the next week, "Love Yourself" was replaced at the top by <a href="/wiki/Rihanna" title="Rihanna">Rihanna</a>'s "<a href="/wiki/Work_(Rihanna_song)" title="Work (Rihanna song)">Work</a>" and descended to number two.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup> By the middle of 2016, the song had sold 1.6&#160;million copies in the U.S.<sup id="cite_ref-us_sales_39-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-us_sales-39">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup> On the chart dated 7 May 2016, "Love Yourself" spent its 23rd consecutive week in the Hot 100's top ten, breaking the record for the most consecutive weeks logged in the top 10 from a song's debut, previously set by <a href="/wiki/Nicki_Minaj" title="Nicki Minaj">Nicki Minaj</a>'s "<a href="/wiki/Starships_(song)" title="Starships (song)">Starships</a>", <a href="/wiki/Maroon_5" title="Maroon 5">Maroon 5</a>'s "<a href="/wiki/Sugar_(Maroon_5_song)" title="Sugar (Maroon 5 song)">Sugar</a>" and Bieber's both "What Do You Mean?" and "Sorry". It has since been passed by <a href="/wiki/The_Chainsmokers" title="The Chainsmokers">The Chainsmokers</a>'s "<a href="/wiki/Closer_(The_Chainsmokers_song)" title="Closer (The Chainsmokers song)">Closer</a>" (20162017), which spent 32 weeks in the top 10.<sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">&#91;40&#93;</a></sup> Additionally, the song spent an eleventh week at the top of the Radio Songs chart.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41">&#91;41&#93;</a></sup> Additionally, on the chart dated 14 May 2016, "Love Yourself" became Bieber's first chart-topper on the <a href="/wiki/Adult_Contemporary_chart" class="mw-redirect" title="Adult Contemporary chart">Adult Contemporary chart</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42">&#91;42&#93;</a></sup> The song was the most-played song in the United States in 2016, with nearly 4&#160;billion audience impressions.<sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>During 2016, "Love Yourself" sold 1.8&#160;million copies in the US, thus being listed seventh on the best-selling songs of the year list. Overall, it has sold 2.7&#160;million copies in the country.<sup id="cite_ref-ussales_3-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ussales-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>"Love Yourself" finished at No. 1 on the Billboard Hot 100 Year-End of 2016 released in December 2016, becoming Bieber's highest charting song on Hot 100 Year-End to date, surpassing "<a href="/wiki/Boyfriend_(Justin_Bieber_song)" title="Boyfriend (Justin Bieber song)">Boyfriend</a>" on the Hot 100 Year-End of 2012. This made him the youngest artist to date to receive a No. 1 single on a Hot 100 Year-End chart in Billboard's history.<sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">&#91;44&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="United_Kingdom">United Kingdom</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Love_Yourself&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: United Kingdom">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>In the United Kingdom, "Love Yourself" debuted at number three on the <a href="/wiki/UK_Singles_Chart" title="UK Singles Chart">UK Singles Chart</a> on 19 November 2015, after the release of <i>Purpose</i>. The following week, it rose to number two before replacing "<a href="/wiki/Sorry_(Justin_Bieber_song)" title="Sorry (Justin Bieber song)">Sorry</a>" at the top of the chart on 4 December 2015. Bieber is the first artist to replace themselves at the chart's summit since <a href="/wiki/Elvis_Presley" title="Elvis Presley">Elvis Presley</a> in 2005. "Love Yourself" marked Bieber's third consecutive chart-topping song in Britain.<sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup> The following week, the song stayed at the top of the chart with 114,000 combined sales and "Sorry" stayed at number two, which made Bieber the first artist ever to knock himself off the top spot with both songs holding at one and 2 for two consecutive weeks.<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup> "Love Yourself" and "Sorry" remained at the same place the next week, which made Bieber the first artist ever to log four weeks at numbers one and 2 consecutively, breaking the record previously held by The Beatles, who logged three consecutive weeks at numbers one and 2 in 196768.<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">&#91;47&#93;</a></sup> "Love Yourself" was beaten to the top by NHS Choir's "<a href="/wiki/A_Bridge_Over_You" class="mw-redirect" title="A Bridge Over You">A Bridge Over You</a>" charity single by nearly 31,000 chart sales.<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">&#91;48&#93;</a></sup> However, the single rose to the number-one spot the next week, logging a fourth week at the summit and claiming the first number-one song of 2016.<sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49">&#91;49&#93;</a></sup> The following week, it remained at number one, making Bieber the first artist on the <a href="/wiki/UK_Singles_Chart" title="UK Singles Chart">UK Singles Chart</a> to occupy the top three spots on the chart at the same time with "Sorry" at number two and "What Do You Mean?" climbing one place to three.<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50">&#91;50&#93;</a></sup> "Love Yourself" spent six non-consecutive weeks at number one.<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51">&#91;51&#93;</a></sup> On 4 January 2016, the Official Charts Company announced that 'Love Yourself' has earned 719,000 combined sales.<sup id="cite_ref-UK_year-end_52-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-UK_year-end-52">&#91;52&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Australia">Australia</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Love_Yourself&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Australia">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>In Australia, "Love Yourself" debuted at number three on the <a href="/wiki/ARIA_Singles_Chart" class="mw-redirect" title="ARIA Singles Chart">ARIA Singles Chart</a>, after the release of <i>Purpose</i>, giving Bieber his fifth top-three single in the country. That week the singer had three songs inside the top ten: "Sorry" (2), "Love Yourself" (3) and "What Do You Mean?" (7).<sup id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-53">&#91;53&#93;</a></sup> Two weeks later, "Love Yourself" was the most streamed track in the country and rose to number two, also it earned a gold certification for sales of over 35,000 copies.<sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54">&#91;54&#93;</a></sup> In its fourth week, the song ascended from two to one, dethroning <a href="/wiki/Adele" title="Adele">Adele</a>'s "<a href="/wiki/Hello_(Adele_song)" title="Hello (Adele song)">Hello</a>" and earning a platinum certification for sales of over 70,000 copies. With that, Bieber became the only act to have two number-one songs in 2015 following previous single "What Do You Mean?", which topped the chart during four consecutive weeks in September.<sup id="cite_ref-chartstoppedbyLY_55-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-chartstoppedbyLY-55">&#91;55&#93;</a></sup> The song stayed at the top of the chart the following two weeks. On its third week at number one, Bieber's 'Sorry' and "What Do You Mean?" were at number two and eight, respectively. With that, Bieber became the first act to dominate the top two positions since <a href="/wiki/Macklemore_%26_Ryan_Lewis" title="Macklemore &amp; Ryan Lewis">Macklemore &amp; Ryan Lewis</a> did in 2013 with "<a href="/wiki/Same_Love" title="Same Love">Same Love</a>" and "<a href="/wiki/Thrift_Shop" title="Thrift Shop">Thrift Shop</a>". He also was the first act to have three singles inside the chart's top ten since 2012.<sup id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-56">&#91;56&#93;</a></sup> The song was the first number-one song of 2016 and has spent seven consecutive weeks at number one, which places Bieber at number 8 on the list for the most accumulated weeks (11) at number one in the 2010s. Also, it is his longest-running number-one single in Australia.<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-57">&#91;57&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58">&#91;58&#93;</a></sup> "Love Yourself" also topped the charts in Sweden, Ireland, New Zealand, Netherlands and Denmark.<sup id="cite_ref-chartstoppedbyLY_55-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-chartstoppedbyLY-55">&#91;55&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Music_video">Music video</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Love_Yourself&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Music video">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Purpose:_The_Movement">Purpose: The Movement</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Love_Yourself&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Purpose: The Movement">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The song's music video was released on YouTube on November 14, 2015, along with the other videos from "Purpose: The Movement". The video starts with Bieber saying: "Love isn't 'do this for me and I'm going to do this for you.' That's not what love is. Love is just 'I'm gonna do this for you because I wanna do this for you.'"<sup id="cite_ref-59" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-59">&#91;59&#93;</a></sup> Later, the video features husband and wife dancers Keone and Mari Madrid dancing their way through their house. They are later seen dancing on their phone screens. The video ends when the wife wakes up and finds a note on her husband's pillow saying, "Love Yourself".<sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-60">&#91;60&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>As of November 2018, the music video has received over 1.4&#160;billion views on <a href="/wiki/YouTube" title="YouTube">YouTube</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-61">&#91;61&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Live_performances_and_covers">Live performances and covers</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Love_Yourself&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Live performances and covers">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tleft"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Justin_Bieber_at_the_BRIT_Awards_2016.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Justin_Bieber_at_the_BRIT_Awards_2016.jpg/220px-Justin_Bieber_at_the_BRIT_Awards_2016.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Justin_Bieber_at_the_BRIT_Awards_2016.jpg/330px-Justin_Bieber_at_the_BRIT_Awards_2016.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Justin_Bieber_at_the_BRIT_Awards_2016.jpg/440px-Justin_Bieber_at_the_BRIT_Awards_2016.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3264" data-file-height="2448" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Justin_Bieber_at_the_BRIT_Awards_2016.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Bieber during his show at <a href="/wiki/2016_Brit_Awards" title="2016 Brit Awards">2016 Brit Awards</a></div></div></div>
<p>Bieber first performed "Love Yourself" on <i><a href="/wiki/The_Ellen_DeGeneres_Show" title="The Ellen DeGeneres Show">The Ellen DeGeneres Show</a></i> during 'Purpose' week release.<sup id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-62">&#91;62&#93;</a></sup> On November 18, 2015, the song was also performed on <i><a href="/wiki/Today_(U.S._TV_program)" title="Today (U.S. TV program)">The Today Show</a></i> along with other tracks from the album.<sup id="cite_ref-63" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-63">&#91;63&#93;</a></sup> Bieber also added the song to the set list of his show on <a href="/wiki/Capital_(radio_network)" title="Capital (radio network)">Capital FM</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Jingle_Bell_Ball#2015" title="Jingle Bell Ball">Jingle Bell Ball 2015</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-64" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-64">&#91;64&#93;</a></sup> He performed the song at the <a href="/wiki/58th_Annual_Grammy_Awards" title="58th Annual Grammy Awards">58th Annual Grammy Awards</a>. The singer performed an acoustic version of the track with <a href="/wiki/James_Bay_(singer)" title="James Bay (singer)">James Bay</a> on the guitar before performing "Sorry" during the <a href="/wiki/2016_Brit_Awards" title="2016 Brit Awards">2016 Brit Awards</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-65" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-65">&#91;65&#93;</a></sup> He also performed an acoustic version of the song during the <a href="/wiki/3rd_iHeartRadio_Music_Awards" class="mw-redirect" title="3rd iHeartRadio Music Awards">3rd iHeartRadio Music Awards</a> before proceeding to a full performance of "<a href="/wiki/Company_(Justin_Bieber_song)" title="Company (Justin Bieber song)">Company</a>".<sup id="cite_ref-66" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-66">&#91;66&#93;</a></sup> "Love Yourself" is also part of the set list of his <a href="/wiki/Purpose_World_Tour" title="Purpose World Tour">Purpose World Tour</a>. The performance has Bieber on acoustic guitar while seated on a red velvet couch down center stage.<sup id="cite_ref-ew_67-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ew-67">&#91;67&#93;</a></sup> He performed the song at <a href="/wiki/2016_Radio_Disney_Music_Awards" title="2016 Radio Disney Music Awards">Radio Disney Music Awards</a> during a special pocket show for fans, previously recorded.<sup id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-68">&#91;68&#93;</a></sup> On June 4, 2017, Bieber performed "Love Yourself" at the <i><a href="/wiki/One_Love_Manchester" title="One Love Manchester">One Love Manchester</a></i> benefit concert for the victims of the <a href="/wiki/2017_Manchester_Arena_bombing" class="mw-redirect" title="2017 Manchester Arena bombing">2017 Manchester Arena bombing</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69">&#91;69&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Canadian singer <a href="/wiki/Alessia_Cara" title="Alessia Cara">Alessia Cara</a> posted a video covering of the song on her <a href="/wiki/YouTube" title="YouTube">YouTube</a> channel on November 14, 2015.<sup id="cite_ref-70" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-70">&#91;70&#93;</a></sup> English singer <a href="/wiki/Conor_Maynard" title="Conor Maynard">Conor Maynard</a> also posted a video covering the song on his YouTube channel on November 17, 2015.<sup id="cite_ref-71" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-71">&#91;71&#93;</a></sup> American singer <a href="/wiki/Halsey_(singer)" title="Halsey (singer)">Halsey</a> also performed a cover version for <a href="/wiki/Triple_J" title="Triple J">Triple J</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Like_a_Version" title="Like a Version">Like a Version</a> studio in Australia on February 4, 2016.<sup id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-72">&#91;72&#93;</a></sup> Her version garnered attention since she replaced "love yourself" with "fuck yourself."<sup id="cite_ref-73" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-73">&#91;73&#93;</a></sup> British singers Yo Preston and Kelly Kiara teamed up to write a reply to the song, with the version being called "Love Yourself vs F*ck Yourself." In their version, Kiara responds to Bieber's lyrics taking about the boy's cheating habits and overwhelming jealousy.<sup id="cite_ref-elitedaily_74-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-elitedaily-74">&#91;74&#93;</a></sup> Their version charted on the <a href="/wiki/ARIA_Charts" title="ARIA Charts">ARIA Charts</a>, reaching the top-twenty, peaking at number 16.<sup id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-75">&#91;75&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The song was also covered by American pop punk band <a href="/wiki/Grayscale_(band)" title="Grayscale (band)">Grayscale</a> for <a href="/wiki/Punk_Goes_Pop_Vol._7" title="Punk Goes Pop Vol. 7">Punk Goes Pop Vol. 7</a>, a compilation album of covers, which was released by <a href="/wiki/Fearless_Records" title="Fearless Records">Fearless Records</a> on July 14, 2017.
</p>
